="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">h Energy responded to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">both consul</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tations</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, strongly supporting the introduction of robust, well-defined and durable</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> sustainability standards</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (see response to Question 4)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and DECC has</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> now issued </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">its </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">response</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">welcome</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> DECC</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’s decision</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to set out a traject</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ory of decreasing emissions intensities for plants to be eligible for support under the RO</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We are however disappointed that DECC has </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">only given certainty to developers, investors and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">lenders to 2027 and has not agreed to grandfather the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> GHG targets or oth</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">er aspects of the sustainability criteria </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for the duration of support under the RO.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> This creates a project risk which will increase the difficulties in, and costs of, raising finance for new biomass CHP plants.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">E</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">xtensive research into </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">both </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">life-cycle and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">time-dependant methodologies </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">was commissioned by Forth Energy </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">calculating </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">GHG emissions </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">from</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> its three planned biomass plants.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> The comments</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> below</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> on methodology and individual components o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">f the GHG </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">calculation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> are based on this research.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Methodology</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The carbon life-cycle </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">approach</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is the basis for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">both the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">EC</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> methodology and Ofgem</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> GHG life-cycle tool</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. It</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is established, well understood and widely used and should continue to form the measurement basis for GHG emissions from biomass. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Government should </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">continue to explore </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the contribution that the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">time</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">dependant methodology</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> can make to the assessm</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ent of GHG emission savings.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> It</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> builds on the life-cycle </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">approach and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> adds a time element to provide a deeper understanding of the scop</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and profile of, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">carbon reductions </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">over the lifetime of a project</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> as compared to conventional fossil fuel energy generation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Forth Energy commissioned the Scottish Institute for Sustainable Technology (SISTech) to undertake a time-dependant study o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">f the carbon emissions from the proposed Grangemouth biomass CHP plant under a range </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of realistic fuelling scenarios</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. The study included all emissions from land-use change, harvesting, processing, transportation and combustion of the biomass fuel, netting</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> off the CO2 absorbed by subsequent biomass regrowth. It found that the Grangemouth biomass plant can deliver atmospheric CO2 savings within five to eight years (depending on the biomass type and source location) compared to a state-of-the-art gas-fired CH</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">P plant. Over the 20 year minimum lifetime of the plant, the cumulative atmospheric CO2 reduction compared to a new gas CHP plant is in the order of 4 to 7 Mt.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Relative to a coal fired plant or the EU fossil-fired standard the savings occur earlier and are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> significantly higher.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Components </span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Conversion efficiency - T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">verall saving from each</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> step of the GHG lifecycle calculation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is dependent on the specific supply chain of any given fuel</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ling</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> scenario, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">however, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the conversion efficiency </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">from fuel to energy </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is one aspect that will have an effect on all scenarios, with higher plant efficiencies delivering lower emissions. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">For example, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Forth Energy’s proposed CHP plant at Grangemouth can deliver primary energy savings</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (i.e. fuel </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">consumption and emissions </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">saving</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in the order of 24%. T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he support mechanisms for renewable energy should promote the efficient use of fuel and should therefore </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">provide </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">greater support and certainty to CHP plants than to electricity </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">or heat </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">only plants.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Indirect land use - </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Evaluating i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ndirect land use change (iLUC) is not stipulated within the su</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">stainability criteria</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t is not certain what would occur if biomass was not used for energy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> production</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Forth Energy shares the Government’s view</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that the majority of biomass fuel availabl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e in the current market will come from forestry and ind</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ustrial residues where iLUC</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is unlikely to occur</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. It is also agreed that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">“increased demand for woodfuel could encourage undermanaged forests being brought under active management which would provide ad</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ditional timber and woodfuel supplies for manufacturing and construction as well as for energy use.”</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> This would result in biodiversity benefits and business opportunities in rural areas.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Forth Energy </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">believes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t is more</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> important</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">focus on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">polici</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">es which promote </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">good forest management practices.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Question 4 - </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">There are sustainability </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">guidelines for biomass, do these go far enough?</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Forth Energy welcomes DEFRA proposals on the implementation of the EU’s Timber Regulations which aim to further </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">reduce the risk of illegally harvested timber being place</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> on, or traded within the European Union market</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It also broadly welcomes the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> UK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Government’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">final </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">proposals</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to introduce new sustainability </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">criteria and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">reporting</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> requirements from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">April 2014</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">eplacing the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">European Commission</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">enewable </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">E</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nergy </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">D</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">irective (RED) Land C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">riteria with</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sustainable forest management criteria based upon the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">UK Government’s public procurement policy for wood.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Monitoring land use, quality and species</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Forth Energy agree</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s with DECC’s expectation that, “the price premium that saw-logs command in the market will prevent their use in power generation.” The decision on the quality of wood to be used in power gene</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ration is therefore</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> self-regulating. We agree with DECC that no </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">intervention within the timber market is currently required indeed, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">any regulation could adversely impact the revenue stream options for the forestry industry and may prevent the use of whole trees that are unsu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">itable</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e.g.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> diseased trees</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, forest thinnings</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">saw-logs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Although there is no evidence that significant volumes of high quality virgin wood are being diverted from the wood processing sector, we </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">agree with DECC’s decision</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to monitor the quality of timber being used in the energy sector. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Land use</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">change</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> and wider issues</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Forth Energy considers </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DECC’s decision to introduce </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sustainable forest management criteria based on</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> public procurement policy for wood will</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> help to address</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> land</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> use change </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and wider </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">issues,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in particular: sustainab</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">le harvest rates and carbon stocks, deforestation, biodiversit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">y and social impacts</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. These matters are explicitly addressed in the policy’s def</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">inition document for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Legal and Sustainable</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.’</span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Government should to continue working with its European Partne</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rs to ensure that all aspects of sustainability are appropriately addressed through the application of a “harmonized and binding sustainability criteria for biomass.”</span><a name="_ftnref15"></a><a href="#_ftn15">[15]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Question 5 - </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What will the local environmental impacts (for example air pollution) be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">from the use heat generation in urban areas, for example CHP units?</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Biomass CHP has a number of advantages as a source of energ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">y; it is a proven technology,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> provides renewable base load electricity and if managed carefully a number of environmental and sustainability benefits, the most significant of which is the reduction in carbon emissions compared to current grid mix and fossil fuels</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Regulatory control </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">of environmental i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">mpacts</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The development and operation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">large-scale </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CHP plants</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and district heat networks in the UK are governed by a statutory framework which requires a number of permissions and licences to be secured</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> prior to operation and substantial</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> monitoring and reporting during operation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">They</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> adequately</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> assess and control the environmental impact of these developments</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref16"></a><a href="#_ftn16">[16]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Impacts related to delivery of wood fuel</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Small biomass fuelled CHP and heat only plants in urban area</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s would have small</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> fuel s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tores which would require</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to be refilled </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">regularly </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">by HGV’s. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This would result </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in increased local traffic and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> has the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">potential</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to cause </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">an increase in traffic noise</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> result</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in a negative impact on air quality.  In contrast fuel delivered by ship</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (a low-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">carbon form of transportation)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">large</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">scale </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CHP plants at port locations </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">does not suffer from these problems</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Operational impact</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Small-scale CHP plants can</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> make a contribution to renewable heat provision in rural or low density areas</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> on an </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">individual premises or residence basis </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">however </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">such plants are less compatible with urban communities where they can add to air quality challenges</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref17"></a><a href="#_ftn17">[17]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Larger-scale CHP plants, fitted with high-quality air filtering systems, represent a viable source of renew</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">able heat in urban </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">areas</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">where demand is high.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">They promote the use of heat created directly from the combustion of renewable fuels in large, efficient boilers and distributed to consumers via dedicated heat networks</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Economic impact</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The development of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">la</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rge</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">scale </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CHP plants and the associated heat networks </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">can</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">bring </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">substantial </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">economic benefits to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">urban areas. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Forth Energy’s plants</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, for example,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> represent a combined investment in renew</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">able energy capacity</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of £1.1 billion and are expected to bring economi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">c growth to the regions in which they are located of around £80 million per annum (measured as Gross Value Added). They will create approximately 1000 construction jobs over 3 years and 210 permanent jobs throughout their operational life</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref18"></a><a href="#_ftn18">[18]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As well as pro</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">viding process heat and cooling to existing industrial facilities, Forth Energy’s large-scale CHP plants could attract inward investment to their industrial hinterlands from companies seeking supplies of reliable, renewable, low-carbon energy. Feasibility </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">studies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> have been conducted into the construction of a district heating network from each plant, providing low-carbon heating and hot-water to domestic and commercial premises</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref19"></a><a href="#_ftn19">[19]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> This potential for industrial clusters to realise carbon benefits and support </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">further industrial development has been recognised by DECC. </span><a name="_ftnref20"></a><a href="#_ftn20">[20]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Question 7 - </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Why is community heating/CHP n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ot more common in the UK?</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DECC recognises</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> role for heat networks in urban areas</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><a name="_ftnref21"></a><a href="#_ftn21">[21]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> whilst the UK Committee on Climate Change recognises that district heating utilising, low carbon generation or waste heat in high density areas, is one of the most cost effective forms of carbon abatement.</span><a name="_ftnref22"></a><a href="#_ftn22">[22]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Forth Energy </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">commissioned the Fraser of Allande</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">r Institute (FOAI), University of Strathclyde Business School </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">explore public policy measures that could be implemented to assist in the delivery of Government’s renewable energy targets</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. As part of this commission FOAI identified the following barriers </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and issues as causes for the slow development of ren</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ewable heat in Scotland (and this can be extended to the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> UK):</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">competition from natural gas as a relatively cheap and convenient fuel source;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the high capital costs of installing many forms of renewable he</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">at</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">District heating continues to face the economic challenges associated with retrofit and the ongoing uncertainty of RHI support which currently specifically excludes from investment in DH pipework</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the lack of infrastructure to deliver heat (as opposed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to electricity or gas) to customers;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">significantly higher public subsidies for renewable electricity than renewable heat (resulting in the use of biomass and waste predominantly for electricity generation)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">investment and development risks created by uncer</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tainties in the amount and duration of financial support that might be available under the Renewable Heat Incentive</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the convenience and controllability of electricity, gas, and LPG as heating sources compared to some forms of renewable heat</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">limited and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">uncertain long term supply of indigenous biomass and waste and the limited scope for alternative low-carbon heating technologies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">lengthy planning and consenting timescales for larger schemes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">existing market structures, energy delivery systems, energy com</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">panies, and customer behaviour and understanding create significant inertia in the market.  Existing systems will tend to persist unless there are major stimu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">li</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to trigger or support change; and</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ack of a joined up low</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">carbon heat strategy with major polic</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">y measures, political backing, and significant financial resources</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">To achieve the Scottish Government (and UK Government) renewable energy targets three aspects must be addressed in parallel:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The production of renewable heat;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Infrastructure to allow the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">efficient delivery of heat;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Consumer take-up of renewable heat.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Forth Energy considers that the following matters are crucial to ensure the development of a heat industry that can provide “affordable, secure and low carbon heatin</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">g,”</span><a name="_ftnref23"></a><a href="#_ftn23">[23]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in particula</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">promote the development of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">large</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">scale biomass CHP plants in urban and industrial areas.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Policies and proposals which strongly promote the deployment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> biomass CHP plants, by increasing certainty and reducing the risks faced by developer</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s, investors a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nd lenders;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Regulatory certainty and stability to provide the certainty that is needed by developers, lenders and investors </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to develop biomass CHP schemes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, including:</span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 85.05pt; padding-left:4.95pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a specific RHI tariff for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">renewable </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CHP</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> plants</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 85.56pt; padding-left:4.44pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e ability to confirm the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">RHI </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tariff an</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d availability of budget through </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">an </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Enhanced Preliminary Accreditation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> process</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 84.43pt; padding-left:5.57pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">support under the CfD framework</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> which </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">provides</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a return on investment commensurate with project risks,</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 85.56pt; padding-left:4.44pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">grandfathered sust</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ainability criteria for biomass;</span></li></ol><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Promotion of heat </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">strategies by local authorities and stakeholder engagement to maximise the potential for development of district heat networks;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-h